36:32.870 --> 36:40.098
and it started selling right away, so I bought another 500, and it kept selling.

36:40.599 --> 36:47.186
Then I ended up buying about 2,000 of it altogether, because it just kept selling.

36:47.206 --> 36:50.430
It was like 40, 50 a week, and I had to run with a winner.

36:50.450 --> 36:51.591
And this is the pay-per-view?

36:51.631 --> 36:53.493
No, the hardback, 395.

36:53.613 --> 36:53.773
Wow.

36:54.794 --> 36:56.336
Okay.

36:56.356 --> 37:01.662
Then I called Harcourt for us to try and get another 500, because I kept pumping up my stock, you know?

37:02.114 --> 37:10.302
And the gal says to me, oh, the white sale's over, you can't have them anymore.

37:10.482 --> 37:18.309
So I said, well, you know, we did buy 2,000, and it's just the white sale's over in a couple of days.

37:18.329 --> 37:20.011
I'll tell you what, can I make a special deal with you and get 1,000 more?

37:20.271 --> 37:21.993
She says, well, I'll have to check.

37:22.013 --> 37:24.115
And she comes back, and she says, OK, you get 1,000 more.

37:25.816 --> 37:26.737
Mind you, I'm paying you $2 each.

37:26.757 --> 37:31.682
So I get the 1,000 in, and about three weeks later,

37:32.405 --> 37:35.568
Marlboro has them for $1.95.

37:38.911 --> 37:39.812
They dump the rest.

37:40.372 --> 37:42.895
So mind you, I had paid her $2.

37:42.995 --> 37:48.280
Now Marlboro is offering it for $1.95, that's 50%, so I can buy it from a dollar.

37:50.102 --> 37:57.408
So I place an order with Marlboro for another $1,000, and he gives them for me at $0.80 each.

37:57.428 --> 38:02.293
And I call Harper at this, and I said, look, you know, you charge me $2 for the book, and

38:02.712 --> 38:16.886
Now I get it for 80 cents.

38:16.906 --> 38:19.048
This isn't right.

38:19.069 --> 38:21.151
And she said, well, you're a tough one.

38:21.171 --> 38:26.016
So I had to go all the way up to Janovich, and he finally told her to keep me happy.

38:26.036 --> 38:26.436
That's a fair story.

38:26.456 --> 38:27.537
You could have just returned those books, actually.

38:27.557 --> 38:27.937
Well, you couldn't.

38:27.957 --> 38:28.538
It was a white sale.

38:28.878 --> 38:29.479
It was a white sale.

38:29.746 --> 38:35.699
I mean, in total, I probably got about 5,000, 6,000 copies on this remainder.

38:35.719 --> 38:39.087
Now, it took three, four years, five years or something.

38:39.107 --> 38:42.134
We finally sold them out.

38:42.154 --> 38:44.920
Now, we bought it as a new paperback.

38:45.659 --> 38:50.084
And we're selling it at a discount, what, from $6.95 to $7.95.

38:50.104 --> 38:51.206
And we're still selling it.

38:51.226 --> 38:53.749
And in fact, I'll give you a quota to that story.

38:53.829 --> 38:54.770
No, we're still selling.

38:54.810 --> 39:03.701
Well, when I went to Italy in November, I bought my copy here, because I needed it, and I wanted to read it before I entered it, and just ran at it.

39:04.201 --> 39:05.162
And I think I paid $7.98.

39:05.222 --> 39:05.623
$7.95, yeah.

39:05.643 --> 39:12.811
So that was, you know, I mean, partially it was a bestseller for me, because I got all the copies.

39:12.831 --> 39:14.113
There are other books that I got.

39:14.431 --> 39:17.976
5,000 copies of them.

39:18.637 --> 39:25.066
Do you do a lot of new books that you buy directly from the publisher?

39:25.186 --> 39:30.113
